1. Ratio of Fibonacci numbers

a.

Write two different R functions which return the sequence ri = Fi+1 /Fi for i = 1, . . . , n where Fi is the ith Fibonacci number, once using for and once using while.

For understanding the sequence, it is as follows
Fibonacci sequence: 0,1,1,2,3,5,8,13,21,…, with 0 as F0

  • r1 = F2/F1 = 1/1 = 1
  • r2 = F3/F2 = 2/1 = 2
  • r3 = F4/F3 = 3/2 = 1.5

For loop

fib_ratio_for <- function(n) {
  # Check for bad inputs
  if (n <= 0) {
    stop("Input 'n' cannot be 0 or negative.")
  } else if (n == 1) {
    # Catch case of n = 1 due to a leading error if not implemented
    return(1)
  } else {
    # numeric vector created with length n + 1 
    # to store the Fibonacci sequence up to the (n + 1)th element.
    fibonacci <- numeric(n + 1) 
    # Assign values (1,1) as first two elements
    fibonacci[1:2] <- c(1, 1)
    # for loop that iterates over the sequence 3:(n + 1)
    # starting from 3 because first two elements are already declared
    for (i in 3:(n + 1)) {
      # Assigning Fibonacci rule to get the next number out of the last two
      fibonacci[i] <- fibonacci[i - 1] + fibonacci[i - 2]
    }
    # Finally calculate the ratio of each fibonacci number
    ratios <- fibonacci[2:(n + 1)] / fibonacci[1:n]
    return(ratios)
  }
}

Execute for loop:

fib_ratio_for(5)
## [1] 1.000000 2.000000 1.500000 1.666667 1.600000

While loop

fib_ratio_while <- function(n) {
  if (n <= 0) {
    stop("Input 'n' cannot be 0 or negative.")
  } else if (n == 1) {
    return(1)
  } else {
    fibonacci <- numeric(n + 1)
    fibonacci[1:2] <- c(1, 1)
    i <- 3
    while (i <= n + 1) {
      fibonacci[i] <- fibonacci[i - 1] + fibonacci[i - 2]
      i <- i + 1
    }
    ratios <- fibonacci[2:(n + 1)] / fibonacci[1:n]
    return(ratios)
  }
}

Execute while loop:

fib_ratio_while(7)
## [1] 1.000000 2.000000 1.500000 1.666667 1.600000 1.625000 1.615385

Explanation for statistics given from microbenchmark
min: Minimum time it took to execute
lq: Lower quartile (25th percentile) time it took to execute
mean: Mean time it took to execute
median: Median time it took to execute
uq: Upper quartile (75th percentile) time it took to execute
max: Maximum time it took to execute
neval: Number of times each expression was evaluated

Answer: As given from the stats, the function using the for loop is faster.

2. Gamma function

compute_rho <- function(n) { if (n <= 0) { stop(“n must be a positive integer”) }

if (n == 1) { return(0) # ρ1 is defined as 0 }

# Compute the logarithmic form of the ratio log_rho <- lgamma((n - 1) / 2) - lgamma(1/2) - lgamma((n - 2) / 2)

# Convert the result back to the regular scale rho <- exp(log_rho)

return(rho) }

b. Observing behavior for n = 2000

n <- 2000 rho_2000 <- compute_rho(n) print(rho_2000) # Explanation: For large values of n, the gamma function overflows due to its computational limitations.

c. Implementation for large values of n

Function to compute rho_n using gamma function

compute_rho <- function(n) { if (n %% 2 != 0) { numerator <- gamma((n - 1)/2) denominator <- gamma(1/2) * gamma((n - 2)/2) return(numerator / denominator) } else { stop(“n must be an odd positive integer.”) } }

Function to compute rho_n for large values of n

compute_large_rho <- function(n) { if (n %% 2 != 0) { # Handling large values of n using log-gamma numerator <- lgamma((n - 1)/2) denominator <- lgamma(1/2) + lgamma((n - 2)/2) return(exp(numerator - denominator)) } else { stop(“n must be an odd positive integer.”) } }

Testing the functions

n <- 1001 print(compute_rho(n)) print(compute_large_rho(n))

3. The golden ratio

a. Computing Φn+1 using recursion

phi_recursive <- function(n) { if (n == 0) { return(sqrt(5) + 1)/2 } else if (n == 1) { return(sqrt(5) + 3)/2 } else { return(phi_recursive(n - 1) + phi_recursive(n - 2)) } }

b. Computing Φn+1 using power operator

phi_power <- function(n) { phi <- (sqrt(5) + 1)/2 return(phi^(n + 1)) }

c. Comparing results

n_values <- c(12, 60, 120, 300)

for (n in n_values) { result_a <- phi_recursive(n) result_b <- phi_power(n)

# Using == operator comparison1 <- result_a == result_b

# Using all.equal function comparison2 <- all.equal(result_a, result_b)

cat(“For n =”, n, “”) cat(“Using == operator:”, comparison1, “”) cat(“Using all.equal function:”, comparison2, “”) }

4. Game of craps

A variation of game of craps is played as follows. The player rolls a die and if they roll a 6, they immediately wins. If a 1 is rolled, they immediately loses. If a 2, 3, 4, or 5 is rolled, then this number becomes their “point number.’ ’ The player then has up to three more rolls of the die to roll their point number again. If they do, they win otherwise they lose. Write a program in R to simulate a game of craps. Explain the steps of your program. If the code is not explained, no points will be earned.

# Define the function for a game of crabs
game_of_craps <- function(){
    # Function to get a random number between 1 and 6 i.e. rolling the dice once
    dice_number <- floor(runif(1, min=1, max=7))
    # check for win or lose condition in first attempt
    if (dice_number == 1){
      return("Sorry, you lost!")
    }
    else if (dice_number == 6){
      return("Yeah, you won in the first attempt!")
    }
    else {
      # for loop to have three more attempts to roll the same 'point number'
      for (i in 1:3){
        # Function to get a random number between 1 and 6 i.e. rolling the dice once
        new_dice_number <- floor(runif(1, min=1, max=7))
        # Check for same 'point number'
        if (dice_number == new_dice_number){
          return("Yeah, you won rolling the same 'point number' again!")
        }
    }
  } 
  return("Sorry, you lost after three more attempts!")
}

# Execute function i.e. one simulation of the game
game_of_craps()
## [1] "Yeah, you won rolling the same 'point number' again!"

Solution

a. Explain the code

The code initially generates an random variable x defined by a normal distribution with mean and standard deviation of 1. Then, it generates another noise variable with the same characteristics as x and y is a combination of x, the noise and a constant of 2.

Each step consist of r selecting different sections of the data frame df with a proportion of 75% to 25% for training and testing respectively and calculate the root mean square error for each step. The error for each steps are 1.0249956, 0.9952113, 1.06855, 1.0707264 and the biggest gap between the errors is 0.0755151, what is doesn’t looks like outstanding.

b. Readability

From the code we can notice a few things:

  • The code is repeating itself a few times and run it in a loop or call functions to avoid code repetition would make it more readable.
  • The code could write more comments in the code to give us an abstraction of what he is planning to do and inline comment to give us specific details, like the definition of the variable x.
  • Use meaningful names can make it easier to understand the code, like pred1, instead of p1.

c. Wrap Function

Change the code according to a. and wrap it in a function. This function should have at most 10 lines (without adding commands to more lines such as x <- 1; y <- 2. Such commands will count as 2 lines!). Check that the function called on the same input outputs the same as the provided code.

# Define the function

linear_models <- function(df, formula, steps = 4) {
  # Create an empty vector to store the errors
  r <- numeric()
  step = nrow(df)/steps
  # Loop through the steps
  for (i in 1:steps) {
    cat("Step", i, "\n")
    section <- ((i-1)*step+1):(i*step)
    fit <- lm(formula, data = df[-section,]) # Fit the model
    p <- predict(fit, newdata = df[section,]) # Predict the model
    r <- c(r, sqrt(mean((p - df[section,"y"])^2)))
  }
  return(r)
}

set.seed(1)
x <- rnorm(1000)
y <- 2 + x + rnorm(1000)
df <- data.frame(x, y)

# Execute the function

linear_models(df, y ~ x)

6. Measuring and improving performance

Have a look at the code of the function below. It is a function for performing a Kruskal Wallis test, a robust non-parametric method for testing whether samples come from the same distribution. (Note: we assume no missing values are present in x).

kwtest <- function (x, g, ...)
{
  if (is.list(x)) {
    if (length(x) < 2L)
      stop("'x' must be a list with at least 2 elements")
    if (!missing(g))
      warning("'x' is a list, so ignoring argument 'g'")
    if (!all(sapply(x, is.numeric)))
      warning("some elements of 'x' are not numeric and will be coerced to numeric")
    k <- length(x)
    l <- lengths(x)
    if (any(l == 0L))
      stop("all groups must contain data")
    g <- factor(rep.int(seq_len(k), l))
    x <- unlist(x)
}
else {
  if (length(x) != length(g))
    stop("'x' and 'g' must have the same length")
  g <- factor(g)
  k <- nlevels(g)
  if (k < 2L)
    stop("all observations are in the same group")
}
n <- length(x)
if (n < 2L)
  stop("not enough observations")
r <- rank(x)
TIES <- table(x)

STATISTIC <- sum(tapply(r, g, sum)^2/tapply(r, g, length))
STATISTIC <- ((12 * STATISTIC/(n * (n + 1)) - 3 * (n + 1))/(1 -
  sum(TIES^3 - TIES)/(n^3 - n)))
PARAMETER <- k - 1L

PVAL <- pchisq(STATISTIC, PARAMETER, lower.tail = FALSE)
names(STATISTIC) <- "Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared"
names(PARAMETER) <- "df"
RVAL <- list(statistic = STATISTIC, parameter = PARAMETER,
  p.value = PVAL, method = "Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test")
return(RVAL)
}

Solution

a. Pseudo code

This is a test

kwtest_pseudo <- function (x, g, ...)
{
  if x is a list {
    if x has less than 2 elements
      Do not continue with the code and inform the user
    if g is provided
      Give a warning to the user that g will be ignored
    if all the elemensts of x are not numeric
      Warns the users that some elements are not numeric and will be converted 
      to numeric
    k <- length(x)
    l <- lengths(x)
    if any element of x is 0
      Stop and inform that all the groups should contain data
    g <- factor(rep.int(seq_len(k), l))
    x <- unlist(x)
  }
  if x is not a list {
    if the length of x and g are different
      Stops and inform the user x and g should be the same length
    g <- factor(g)
    k <- nlevels(g)
    if there are less than 2 groups in g
      Stop and inform the user
  }
  n <- length(x)
  if x length is less than 2
    Stop and inform about the lack of observations
  r <- rank(x)
  TIES <- table(x)
  STATISTIC <- Calculate the Kruskal-Wallis statistic
  PARAMETER <- degree of freedom
  PVAL <- pchisq(STATISTIC, PARAMETER, lower.tail = FALSE)
  names(STATISTIC) <- "Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared"
  names(PARAMETER) <- "df"
  RVAL <- list(statistic = STATISTIC, parameter = PARAMETER,
  p.value = PVAL, method = "Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test")
  return(RVAL)
  
}

c. kwtest faster

kwtest_fast <- function(x, g, ...) {
  if (!is.numeric(x) | !is.numeric(g)) {
    stop("x and g must be numeric vectors")
  }
  print(x)
  
  if (length(x) != length(g)) {
    print(length(x))
    print(length(g))
    stop("x and g must have the same length")
  }
  
  number_groups <- nlevels(factor(g))
  N <- length(x)
  
  if (number_groups < 2L){
    print(number_groups)
    print(g)
    stop("nlevels(g) < 2 shows all observations are in the same group")
  }
    
  if (N < 2L)
    stop("length(x) has not enough observations")
  
  number_groups <- nlevels(factor(g))
  obs_group <- length(unique(g))
  r <- rank(x)
  r_group_avg <- tapply(r, g, sum)/obs_group
  r_avg <- (N + 1)/2
  
  H_num <-(N - 1) * sum(obs_group * (r_group_avg - r_avg)**2)
  H_dem <- sum((r - r_avg)**2)
  
  H <- H_num/H_dem
  
  pval <- pchisq(H, obs_group - 1, lower.tail = FALSE)
  
  return(pval)
  
}

set.seed(1234)

n <- 50
# number of individuals
X <- matrix(rt(m * n, df = 10), nrow = m)
grp <- rep(1:3, c(20, 20, 10))


kwtest_mult <- function(X, grp) {
  res <- apply(X, 1, function(x) kwtest(x, grp))
}

# Returns all the statistics from res

res <- kwtest_mult(X, grp)

# Extract the p-values

p_values <- sapply(res, function(x) x$p.value)

e. Multiple experiments using for loop

kwtest_matrix2 <- function(X, g) {
  if (!is.matrix(X)) {
    stop("X must be a matrix.")
  }
  if (!is.numeric(g)) {
    stop("g must be a numeric vector")
  }
  if (ncol(X) != length(g)) {
    stop("Number of cols X of matrix have to be as long as length of vector g")
  }
  m <- nrow(X)
  test_statistics <- numeric(m)
  
  for (i in 1:m) {
    # Take data from each row
    experiment_data <- X[i,]
    # Calculate Chi-Square value from Kruskal wallis test and store it in vector
    test_statistics[i] = kwtest_fast(experiment_data, g)
  }
  
  return(test_statistics)
  
}

f. Benchmarking

library(microbenchmark)

# For a better overview set random data from above here again
set.seed(1234)
m <- 1000 # number of repetitions
n <- 50
X <- matrix(rt(m * n, df = 10), nrow = m)
grp <- rep(1:3, c(20, 20, 10))

# Benchmark the two functions
benchmarks <- microbenchmark(
  apply_approach = kwtest_matrix(X, grp),
  loop_approach = kwtest_matrix2(X, grp),
  times = 10
)

# Print the benchmarks
print(benchmarks)
## Unit: milliseconds
##            expr      min       lq     mean   median       uq      max neval
##  apply_approach 190.3217 195.4321 198.8963 197.7316 201.7015 212.6264    10
##   loop_approach 118.2769 123.1258 123.9622 123.9476 126.4805 128.0009    10

As shown from the statistics, the loop approach is faster than the apply approach.

g. Vectorizing

library(microbenchmark)

# For a better overview set random data from above here again
set.seed(1234)
m <- 1000 # number of repetitions
n <- 50
X <- matrix(rt(m * n, df = 10), nrow = m)
grp <- rep(1:3, c(20, 20, 10))

kwtest_vectorize <- function(X, grp) {
  #?Vectorize
  #print(grp)
  # vectorized_kwtest <- Vectorize(kwtest_fast, vectorize.args = "X")
  
  #print(vectorized_kwtest)
  # res <- vectorized_kwtest(X, grp)
  # return(res)
  
  res <- mapply(kwtest, split(X, seq(nrow(X))), MoreArgs = list(grp))
  return(res)
}

# Benchmark the two functions
benchmarks <- microbenchmark(
  apply_approach = kwtest_matrix(X, grp),
  loop_approach = kwtest_matrix2(X, grp),
  vectorize_approach = kwtest_vectorize(X, grp), 
  times = 10
)

# Print the benchmarks
print(benchmarks)
## Unit: milliseconds
##                expr      min       lq     mean   median       uq      max neval
##      apply_approach 182.0587 186.1600 199.0349 198.6220 206.5714 226.5876    10
##       loop_approach 108.9979 114.9421 120.4422 120.2245 125.9423 131.6776    10
##  vectorize_approach 179.8181 183.9840 195.0018 197.9682 203.0304 205.6476    10

Since the Vectorize() uses mapply() under the hood, we can use this function right away to compare the results with the other two approaches. As shown, the loop approach is still the best.
